Grid System for COVID-19 Risk Areas¶

This notebook generates a grid system for counting the number of locations where the risk of the spread of COVID-19 is high.

Hypotheses¶

  • The greater the number of potentially crowded areas, the higher probability of these areas becoming a cluster
  • The areas include:
    • Hawker centres
    • Childcare centres
    • Malls
    • National parks
    • Offices
    • Supermarkets
    • Clinics

Functions¶

Next, we define some helper functions:

def check_grid(pt):
    return df_grid.index[df_grid.grid.apply(lambda x: x.contains(pt))][0]

def c(start, end):
    return list(np.arange(start, end+1))

def check_poly(poly):
    for pa in pa_list:
        for coords in pa_data[pa.upper()]:
            if Polygon(coords).intersects(poly):
                return True
            
    return False

Next, we compute the boundaries of the Singapore map in terms of minimum and maximum latitude and longitude:

min_lat = 1000
max_lat = 0
min_lon = 1000
max_lon = 0

for pa in pa_list:
    temp_dat = pa_data[pa.upper()]
    temp_coords = np.array([]).reshape(0, 2)
    for coords in temp_dat:
        temp_coords = np.vstack([temp_coords, coords])
    
    temp_max_lat = np.max(temp_coords[:, 1])
    temp_min_lat = np.min(temp_coords[:, 1])
    temp_max_lon = np.max(temp_coords[:, 0])
    temp_min_lon = np.min(temp_coords[:, 0])
    
    if temp_min_lat < min_lat:
        min_lat = temp_min_lat
    if temp_max_lat > max_lat:
        max_lat = temp_max_lat
        
    if temp_min_lon < min_lon:
        min_lon = temp_min_lon
    if temp_max_lon > max_lon:
        max_lon = temp_max_lon

Plot Grid¶

Using these boundaries, we define the grid to obtain approximately 750m by 750m grid squares.

# Set coordinates for corners
left_bottom = (min_lon, min_lat)
left_top = (min_lon, max_lat)
right_top = (max_lon, max_lat)
right_bottom = (max_lon, min_lat)

# Set boundaries
bounds = np.array([left_bottom, left_top, right_top, right_bottom, left_bottom])

# Get grid coordinates
cols = np.linspace(min_lon, max_lon, num=73)
rows = np.linspace(min_lat, max_lat, num=47)

# Compute coords for text placement
colshift = cols[1] - cols[0]
rowshift = rows[1] - rows[0]

col_mids = cols + colshift / 10
row_mids = rows + rowshift / 3 * 2

# Check height and width
height = distance((min_lat, min_lon), (rows[1], cols[0])).km
width = distance((min_lat, min_lon), (rows[0], cols[1])).km

We obtain a total of 3,431 grid squares of 0.56 sq. km each.

print('Height: %s km' % round(height, 3))
print('Width: %s km' % round(width, 3))
print('Area: %s sq. km' % str(round(height * width, 3)))
print('No. of Plots: %s' % (cols.shape[0] * rows.shape[0]))

Extract Grid¶

Next, we extract all grid coordinates into a data frame. This well help us to assign grids to all coordinates in the dataset containing all locations of interest.

# Initialise dictionary
all_grids = dict()
counter = 0

# Compute grids
for j in range(cols[:-1].shape[0]):
    for i in range(rows[:-1].shape[0]):
        lb = (cols[j], rows[i])
        lt = (cols[j], rows[i+1])
        rt = (cols[j+1], rows[i+1])
        rb = (cols[j+1], rows[i])
        temp_poly = Polygon([lb, lt, rt, rb])
        if check_poly(temp_poly):
            all_grids['grid'+str(counter)] = temp_poly
        counter += 1

# Convert to data frame
df_grid = pd.DataFrame([all_grids], index=['grid']).T

Merging of Data¶

We merge all the data into a single dataset, and assign a grid number to all locations according to location (latitude/longitude).

# Merge
loc_df = pd.concat([
    hawker, childcare, malls, nparks, offices, supermarkets, clinics
]).reset_index(drop=True)

# Add points
loc_df['pt'] = loc_df[['lat', 'lon']].apply(lambda x: Point((x['lon'], x['lat'])), axis=1)

# Compute grid
loc_df['grid'] = loc_df.pt.apply(check_grid)

Compute Entity Counts¶

To visualise the data, we need gradients representing the count of entities in each grid. To achieve this, we do the following:

  1. Get the entity counts for each grid and location type
  2. Reduce the scale of the entity counts by taking the natural log
  3. Scale the features to the range 0.0 to 0.7 using the MinMaxScaler from Scikit-Learn

This first block of code obtains the counts and also creates a total count for all entities.

# Compute counts per grid
loc_counts = loc_df.groupby(['grid', 'category'])[['category']].count().rename(columns={'category': 'counts'}).reset_index()
loc_counts = loc_counts.pivot_table(index='grid', columns='category', values='counts', aggfunc='sum')
loc_counts['total'] = loc_counts[['childcare', 'office', 'hawker', 'npark', 'mall', 'supermarket', 'clinics']].sum(axis=1)

The next few lines of code performs steps 2 and 3 above.

# Initialise scaler
mms = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0.0,0.6))

# Separate grids
grid_hawker = loc_counts[['hawker']].copy().rename(columns={'hawker': 'vals'})
grid_hawker = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_hawker[['vals']])), index=grid_hawker.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_childcare = loc_counts[['childcare']].copy().rename(columns={'childcare': 'vals'})
grid_childcare = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_childcare[['vals']])), index=grid_childcare.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_mall = loc_counts[['mall']].copy().rename(columns={'mall': 'vals'})
grid_mall = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_mall[['vals']])), index=grid_mall.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_npark = loc_counts[['npark']].copy().rename(columns={'npark': 'vals'})
grid_npark = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_npark[['vals']])), index=grid_npark.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_offices = loc_counts[['office']].copy().rename(columns={'office': 'vals'})
grid_offices = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_offices[['vals']])), index=grid_offices.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_supermarket = loc_counts[['supermarket']].copy().rename(columns={'supermarket': 'vals'})
grid_supermarket = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_supermarket[['vals']])), index=grid_supermarket.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_clinics = loc_counts[['clinics']].copy().rename(columns={'clinics': 'vals'})
grid_clinics = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_clinics[['vals']])), index=grid_clinics.index, columns=['vals'])

grid_total = loc_counts[['total']].copy().rename(columns={'total': 'vals'})
grid_total = pd.DataFrame(mms.fit_transform(np.log1p(grid_total[['vals']])), index=grid_total.index, columns=['vals'])
